OSI Model:

  • OSI model: Open Systems Interconnection
    • 7 layer network model
    • The lesser version of TCP/IP model
    • 7th layer: Application
      • used for applications to communicate.
      • The applications are not apart of the application layer.
      • It the internet protocols such as https and ftp that allow them to communicate.
        Protocols in Application Layer
        • SSH, HTTPS, HTTP, FTP, SNMP, POP3, SMTP, IMAP, DNS
    • 6th layer: Presentation
      • Translates data formats so applications can communicate properly.
      • handles encryption and compression of data.
        Protocols in Presentation Layer
        • MIME, SSL/TLS, ASCII, JPEG, PNG, GIF, MPEG, TIFF, PDF, GZIP, PGP, JPG
    • 5th layer: Session
      • Sets up a session between two computers.
      • maintains sessions
        Functions used by Session Layer
        • RPC: session functions
        • NetBIOS: session functions
        • PPTP: Manages VPN connections
        • SMB: File transfer session management
        • NFS: File transfer for Linux management
    • 4th layer: Transport
      • Chooses protocol to which data will be transferred.
      • TCP vs. UDP
        • TCP: Transmission Control Protocol
          • TCP 3 way handshake which sends Sync packet, then a Syn Ack packages, finally Ack.
          • Aka: Syn, Syn Ack, Ack
          • Reliable transfer which will make sure connection stays connected and that all segments get received with no error.
        • UDP: User Datagram Protocol
          • Non-reliable transfer of data.
          • Faster than TCP
          • Doesn't care if data gets received or not.
          • This is what video services like Skype use!
    • 3rd layer: Network
      • Handles the routing of the request through the internet from router to router.
      • This is called logical addressing and using thinks called IP addresses.
        - IPv4
        - 32-bit addressing which we have ran out of.
        - IPv6
        - 64-bit addressing which has more than enough for every atom in the universe.
        Protocols used for Network Layer
        • IP, IPv4, IPv6, ICMP, ARP, RARP, IGMP, OSPF, BGP, IPsec.
    • 2nd layer: Data Link
      • Handles the physical routing of packets to a specific computer or switch.
      • In side devices that connect to the network are NIC's or Network Interface Cards which all have a MAC or Media Access Control address.
        - You cant change your mac address but you can spoof the address!
        - Checks for errors and makes sure the format is suitable for transmission through a physical medium.
        Protocols for the Data Link Layer
        • Ethernet, IEEE 802.11 Wifi, PPP, HDLC, Frame Relay, ATM, SLIP
    • 1st layer: Physical
      • Handles the physical transmission of data through a wires or other devices such as Bluetooth.
      • Takes care of voltage levels, signals, bit encoding.
        Protocols for the Physical Layer
        • Ethernet, WIFI, Bluetooth, Fiber Optic, DSL, Coaxial Cable, RS-232, USB

Encapsulation

  • As data gets sent to another computer, it gets encapsulated with headers.
    • Once the data has arrived at the other computer, it gets de-encapsulated.
      • This adds a extra layer of security to the data at the bottom of the encapsulation.
  • Stages:
    • Stage One: Application layer adds L7 Header to Data.
    • Stage Two: Presentation layer adds L6 Header to L7 and Data.
    • Stage Three: Session layer adds L5 Header to L6,L7, and Data.
    • Stage Four: Transport layer adds L4 Header to above.
      • Data is now called Segments for TCP and Datagrams for UDP.
    • Stage Five: Network layer adds L3 Header to above.
      • Data is now called Packets.
    • Stage Six: Data Link layer adds 2 headers: L2 and L2 Trailer which goes at the end to say if there were any errors or not.
      • Data is now called Frames.
    • Stage Seven: Encapsulated data is sent across the network.
      • The data is now a stream called Bits.

TCP/IP Model:

  • The TCP/IP model is the first network model which was created to create a standard between networking manufacturers.
    • This is a 4 Layer or 5 Layer Model
      • Officially it is a 4 layer model but some people call it a 5 layer model.
    • Layer 4: Application
      • OSI Model: Application, Presentation, Session
    • Layer 3: Transport
      • OSI Model: Transport
    • Layer 2: Internet
      • OSI Model: Network
    • Layer 1: Network Interface
      • OSI Model: Data Link & Physical
        5 Layer model
        • Some times people split this layer to be 2 layers instead of one.
  • TCP/IP was created by the DoD
    • OSI was created by the ISO (International Organisation for Standardization)

ICMP Packet

  • Internet Control Message Protocol: used for error handling and information exchange between IP networks.
  • ICMP packets are encapsulated by a 20 byte IP header
    • The ICMP packet has its own 8 byte or 32 bit header.
      • Type (8 bits): Type of message such as echo request or echo reply used in Ping.
      • Code (8 bits): Gives different error codes.
      • Checksum (16 bits): Checksum for header and data.
    • Data section of Packet:
      • Depending on the Type it will have transfer information such as timestamps and sequence numbers for successful packets.
      • Or it will have error information such as the header files of failed packets or payload information of the failed packet.
  • Use online documentation for different types and codes and payloads: https://www.iana.org/assignments/icmp-parameters/icmp-parameters.xhtml

Ping Command

  • Used to test a connection between you and a remote resource or device.
  • Ping Sends out ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) echo request packets to the remote device and waits for it to echo replies.
    • This can measure round-trip time and packet loss.
  • Syntax: ping [options] [hostName/Ip address]
  • Graphical Version of Ping: gping hostname

Output:

  • Line 1 => 56 (84) bytes of data:
    • 56 bytes: the ICMP payload without the header
    • 84 bytes: Total Packet Size => ICMP payload (56) + ICMP header (8) + IP header (20) = 84 bytes.
  • Line 2+:
    • 64 bytes: ICMP packet received including the ICMP header
    • from mia09s26-in-f14.1e100.net (142.250.189.142): Domain Name & IP Address for host
      • mia09s26: Miami Server
      • in: Handles incoming requests
      • 1e100.net: domain owned by google, means 1 with 100 zeros afterwards which is the number googol!
    • icmp_seq=1: sequence number that increments for each packet
    • ttl=56: (1 - 255)Time To Live, How many more hops the packet can still make before getting dropped.
    • time=34.4 ms: Round-trip time for the packet to travel from source to destination and back.
  • Statistics Output:
    • 17 packets transmitted: sent ICMP packets
    • 17 received: ICMP packets sent back
    • 0% packet loss: The number of packets lost due to network issues
    • time 16026ms: The total time the ping command was running for
    • rtt: Round Trip Time Stats
      • min 22.215: Fastest rtt received
      • avg 27.978: Average rtt between all packets
      • max 43.701: Slowest rtt received
      • mdev 4.762: Mean/Standard deviation of all packets, Lower values means most of the values are close to the average and that the network is stable and vice-versa.

Basic Use Cases

  • Check DNS Issues: ping hostname
    • If you don't want to check DNS just use the IPaddress.
  • Ping LocalHost & LoopBack: ping (0 || localhost || 127.0.0.1 || ::1 (IPv6))
  • Specify IPv4 or IPv6: ping -(4 || 6) google.com
  • Change Interval Between Pings (default is 1 second): ping -i 0.5 google.com
  • Change Packet Size (default is 56 (84) bytes): ping -s 1000 google.com
    • Does not include Header
  • Flood a Network to Test Performance (requires Sudo): sudo ping -f google.com
    • Sends packets as fast as they will return unless a interval is set!
    • Prints out a "." when a request is sent and prints a "backspace" when a reply is received.
      • This means that you can see visually when packets get dropped because dots will build up.
  • Limit Number of Packets Sent: ping -c 25 google.com
    • By default Windows sends only 4 packets
  • Choose the Number of Packets to Send: ping -n 25 google.com
  • Set Time Limit until Ping Stops (seconds): ping -w 60 google.com
  • Suppress Output of Ping to Only Statistics: ping -q google.com
  • Print Timestamp before each line of Ping Output (Unix format): ping -D google.com
  • Make a noise when the host responds: ping -a google.com
    • Used while fixing a network connection to let you know you have a connection.
  • Change TTL time: ping -t google.com

Advanced Usecases

  • Nmap scan for what hosts exist using ping: ping -b -c 3 -i 20 IPaddress
  • Ping of death attack: ping -s 100 hostname

Errors

  • Timeout: means your request was sent correctly but the destination never sent the echo packet back.
  • Unknown Host: Issue with your input or a mis-configuration on your network such as default gateway.
  • Troubleshooting: Outside in approach
    1. ping Hostname
    2. ping IPaddress
    3. ping router/default gateway
    4. ping localHost
    5. ping loopback

Traceroute Command

  • This command is a diagnostic tool which is used to track the pathway of a packet from the source computer to the destination computer and the time it takes for each section.
    • It uses IP protocols TTL field to get a ICMP message back saying "port unreachable" since the ttl was decremented to zero.
      • It sends 3 UDP probes per hop and displays the rtt for all probes.
      • The first hop gets a TTL of 1 until it gets a response, then it sends the next hop a TTL of 2, etc.
  • In linux the command is traceroute but the windows command is tracert.
    • Linux uses UDP probe packets by default.
    • Windows uses ICMP probes by default.
  • Alternative: mtr "my traceroute" (interactive command)
  • Syntax: traceroute [options] [hostName] [packetLengthOptional]

Probing Methods

  • Use traceroute -M methodName (To choose method)
    • UDP datagrams: With unlikely destination ports starting with 33434 and then incrementing each hope. Since port is unused the ICMP returns "icmp unreach port".
    • ICMP: (-I) Uses echo packets as a probe with the option of raw sockets or dgram sockets.
    • TCP: (-T -p Port) Uses TCP flags to communicate with a device via an allowed port for a protocol for an application.
      • The port is found through a quick port scan. (Default port 80)
      • This is used to bypass firewalls that block unlikely udp ports & icmp echoes.
      • Sends Syn packet: If port is closed you get a tcp reset and for an open port you get syn-ack and you send back a tcp reset.
    • tcpconn: Uses full tcp session opening
    • udp with port: (-U) Trys to bypass firewall; works best with dns (53)
    • udplite: (-UL) Uses different udp format to bypass firewalls using dns (53)
    • dccp: (-D) Uses dccp packets for probes and uses half-open technique like in TCP and uses port 33434.
    • raw: sends raw packet of protocol proto.

Output

  • Header Line 1: traceroute to google.com (192.178.50.46), 30 hops max, 60 byte packets
    • google.com (192.178.50.46): Destination Host => Hostname and IPaddress
    • 30 hops max: Max number of routing hops to probe before quitting.
    • 60 byte packets: Size of packets used.
  • Routing Lines: 7 no-client.rdns.huge-dns.com (74.85.176.1) 18.753 ms 19.293 ms 19.183 ms
    • 7: Hop Number
    • no-client.rdns.huge-dns.com: Resolved Host Name if it can be found.
    • 74.85.176.1: IP address of device
    • 18.753 ms 19.293 ms 19.183 ms: Round trip times for all 3 probes.
  • Exceptions:
    • If the probes come out with different gateway address, then it will print all the address:
      Multiple Gateway Addresses
      • 9 142.251.68.236 (142.251.68.236) 18.991 ms 108.170.234.74 (108.170.234.74) 18.964 ms 74.125.37.156 (74.125.37.156) 19.473 ms
    • If an address cant be found for a probe, a "*" is placed at the beginning for that probe.
      No Address
      • 9 * * *
    • If the response timeouts and so there is no rtt, a "*" is placed in place of its time section ad the end.
      Timeout & No Address
      • 6 * lag-12.tamp20-car1.netops.charter.com (72.31.6.0) 18.176 ms *
